value.0: The old man nods as you approach, inviting you to speak with a tap of his walking stick against the floor.

The old dwarf pauses in his endless pacing. Your eyes can't help but drift to where his sleeve has been stitched closed over a missing arm. He raps his walking stick against the floor, reclaiming your gaze.
"Me face be up here, <lad/lass>... Now, if your business be with things of magic, ye've come to the right place. If your business be otherwise, ye'd best be off and pestering the likes of others."
"Languages be the key to knowledge, <lad/lass>. Myself, I have studied the countless tongues of demons but also am fluent in some of the tongues of men. What is it that you wish translated?"
Leaning his walking stick against his shoulder, he takes your copy of the scribbled message and holds it to the light. "Elven, is it? And in the Exhibits? Well let me see here..."

"Bryn que Cardis Cavanyl d'ru velm a Llorys Brogue, za'et a llandar que moygre eyr qaddara que maar -- If the Cavanaugh Stone gave birth to Brogan's Tears, then to find the mother I must pursue the child."
He scribbles his quick translation onto the back of the original. "Fascinatingly obscure. The elves be like that, I'm afraid. Have you anything else?"
The grizzled old dwarf eyes the figures on the page with interest. "Yes, it be written in the language of the fey, though there is little more I can tell you of it."
"The language is as complex of the fey themselves. Their very alphabet can change from one page to the next and multiple layers of meaning be commonplace..."
"I'm sorry, <lad/lass>, ye'll have to find someone more skilled than I at its translation. Even so, it be a pleasure to witness such a prize. Have ye anything else?"
"Most recent be that fifty-odd band of knights that headed north into the pass... But the term knights be not quite accurate. They struck me as being warrior scholars of a sort."
"Those who came in spoke most knowledgeably of the dark arts and chose from my wares accordingly. Not much of power still be left. Luckily they proved tolerant of my poor, thieving raven."

"Ah, the Cavanaugh Stone," nods the old man. "It not be a hard thing to find seeing how the Clan so foolishly reveres it. The Stone be an evil borne of Stygia, leaving foul waters everywhere it goes."
The dwarf taps his walking stick against the flagstones as he ponders how best to express it. "The Stone doesn't befoul water so much as it slowly draws foul waters to it by and by."
"There be a well behind me place called the Old Man's Well, though I be named more for it than it for me. Long ago, it be a spring of foul waters for that was where the Stone had rested many years."
"Now it be but a well and even that be dry, yet a new spring flows within the Barrow Site where the Stone be kept. Why is that?"
"They draw on the same water of Brogan's Tears. One can even travel between them if ye do not mind the rats. You see, the Cavanaugh Stone, it draws the waters to it."
"Oh now, the well not be mine to claim but, in a manner of speaking, yes. If you follow the foul waters of Brogan's Tears, they will lead you to where the Stone last rested."
"I have seen the demons of that place, <lad/lass>, and this bears their same burning skin and smell of sulfur. It be a cunning thing and the Clan's reverence for it bodes more than ill."
"Why do they do honor to such a rock, placing it on an altar beneath the open sky? Where be the arm of our Clanfather, Brogan? It was in his hand the Stone was found and for him this town be named."
"Yet where be his arm that we rightly should be revering? It be nothing but rot and dust, long ago forgotten. The Cavanaugh Stone be an usurper of Brogan's honor."
You can hear his teeth grinding against each other. "I lost it to a Carpoloth," he finally admits. "A fiend from the Stygian pits. I was still young then, when we fought to collapse the mines."
"Read your history, <lad/lass>! That be why they built the Guild Hall Exhibits, isn't it? To paint it with their veil of lies? ...Well there be things even the Exhibits don't tell, ye hear?"
The old man's eyes look haunted. "Who am I to say if they tell true of Brogan. But of the mines, they say we held the demons at the bridge and collapsed the mines on top of them."
"Our forces at the bridge were slaughtered. The plan had been to shatter it before the hordes arrived but they were already there waiting for us."
"They ambushed us, sweeping the rear lines with devil's fire and only by chance was an old storage room, all full of blasting powder, set alight. Only a handful of us escaped alive."
Reaching for his missing arm, the old dwarf shakes his head sadly. "That's where ye be wrong. It be an ambush, see? They were behind our lines, behind the collapse."
"I said a handful of us escaped, <lad/lass>... But not all of us were dwarves." The room falls quiet with the implications of his tale. The purple haze of incense begins to feel heavy and oppressive.
"I killed the Carpoloth that claimed my arm and destroyed another fiend as it drained the life from my eldest sister. Thirty years later I found and killed another."
"I became a student of their dark arts, their languages, their rituals, that I might better hunt and kill them to the last. To my knowledge, there still be one left that escaped with me that night."
"But enough of an old dwarf's obsessions. Come, there must be brighter topics for us to discuss."
The wizened old man shrinks into his robes. "Potions, craftings, and things arcane, aye. There be power there in the darkened arts, ye see. Enough to destroy the soul of things. Just ask me raven."
With a nod, the old dwarf stares absently over your shoulder at the clutter beyond.

The old man's ears begin to wiggle with anticipation. "Aye, the peril of questions be that someday you'll learn the answers and what then? It will all be over and ye'll be fit for no more than to die."
"Every day of my long, long life," he sighs. He brings the head of his walking stick up, letting it caress your face. "I am sorry to hear of your sacrifice, <lad/lass>."
The one-armed man looks up at you, surprised. "I'm sorry, child. When you asked of them, I only assumed that you could see them too."
"It is said that only those who have sacrificed everything for a cause can see them." He gazes down at his stitched sleeve, his one hand coming over to rub the stump of his shoulder in memory.
He eyes you for a moment, resolving some internal debate. "Then mayhaps the Night Hag has a hand in it. I know what I know but, if she be involved, the gods themselves can't fathom what may happen."
He eyes you for a moment, resolving some internal debate. "Now I can tell ye be a <man/woman> with a whit of sense about ye and ye know enough not to be consorting with one such as the Night Hag..."

"Mayhaps ye can be of service to this old man, yet. Ye be a traveler by the looks of things, which be something I am not. I have long desired to map these Leaks and see what be written in the pattern."
"I have a device here which ye may use to mark them for me. Ye can practice with the ones nearby, if ye wish, but of greater import will be those further afield. Will ye do this for me?"
The old man sighs. "Fine, fine. It be hard to educate the young, these days. No matter. Though not many come here, those who do all be travelers of one sort or another. Will there be anything else?"
The old man sighs. "Ye be as much trouble as me poor Raggletag. Fine, fine, I have more. Here, take it and make use of it where ye can."
Leaning his staff against his shoulder, the old dwarf rustles through his pockets and emerges with the strange device. "There it be. Ye take good care of it, now, and use it well."
Your question seems to give him pause. "The Land of the Dead be a vast place," he begins. "More vast even than the world we come to know in life."
"Many, like Brogan, have crossed into that place. Some have even returned to tell its tale. Worse yet, however, are those things that cross from that world into our own."
The old dwarf pounds his walking stick into the stone floor with such force that the noise seems to echo and rebound forever within his chambers. "I will not grace them with a name," he growls.
The room suddenly grows cold. "...The Night Hag, is it?" The old man's tongue darts out to lick his upper lip. "We've had our dealings... She be of the fey, you know..."
"Strange creatures they be and great power. Many, like the Night Hag, can shift their shape or be in many places at once. But there be one thing that be important if ye be dealing with the fey..."

The old dwarf grips his walking stick tightly. "The fey-borne cannot lie any more than they can tell the truth. They live between such earthly things... If ye must deal with them, ye do so at your peril."
The old man grimaces. "Aye, Raggletag, me poor familiar. I fear me work will be the death of her. She's fallen in love with me infernal contraption, ye see."
"Eh?" he remarks, shaking his grizzled head. "It be a mistake, I should never have crafted it. I was trying to spin gold from thin air... I should have known better to meddle in such things."
In a fit of anger, the one-armed dwarf lashes out with his walking stack, nearly breaking it against one of the bookshelves. "Even when ye succeed, ye fail! Ah, me sorry, poor Raggletag."

"Do ye doubt me, foolish <lad/lass>? Go try it yourself and ye will see. Throw your guilders down the tube and ye will soon find that sometimes even more emerge and sometimes less." His scowl deepens.

"Soon it will leave you a hollow <man/woman>, <lad/lass>, as it did me witless Raggletag. Where she finds her dirty guilders with which to play, I'll never know but she be on a binge again these past few nights."

"She's been clattering up and down the chimney flue so much I can't recall how long it's been since I last slept." The dwarf sighs, looking frail and old. "She'll be home again soon, another guilder in her beak."
The dwarf blinks at you in surprise, his staff still at his side. "Did ye now..."
"Angmar's stash it be, then, and the worst kept secret in all the Arm. I should have known it, I suppose."
The old dwarf bows his weary head. "If the old girl didn't die of shame at being found out, mayhaps she'll be home again soon, another guilder in her beak... The poor dear."
The dwarf blinks at you in surprise, his staff still at his side. "Did ye now..."
The old man grimaces. "Aye, Raggletag, me poor familiar. I fear me work will be the death of her. She's fallen in love with me infernal contraption, ye see."
"Eh?" he remarks, shaking his grizzled head. "It be a mistake, I should never have crafted it. I was trying to spin gold from thin air... I should have known better to meddle in such things."
In a fit of anger, the one-armed dwarf lashes out with his walking stack, nearly breaking it against one of the bookshelves. "Even when ye succeed, ye fail! Ah, me sorry, poor Raggletag."

"Do ye doubt me, foolish <lad/lass>? Go try it yourself and ye will see. Throw your guilders down the tube and ye will soon find that sometimes even more emerge and sometimes less." His scowl deepens.

"Soon it will leave you a hollow <man/woman>, <lad/lass>, as it did me witless Raggletag. At least now I know it be Angmar's gold she spent. I should have known for she be on a binge again these past few nights."
The dwarf sighs, looking frail and old. "If the old girl didn't die of shame at being found out, mayhaps she'll be home again soon, another guilder in her beak... The poor dear."

value.0: <StartAction>[DC: 13]</Start> Choose a tactic to Obtain Favor.

<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> "No, no, child. Not with your fingers all scrunched up like that. You're liable to cramp midway through the casting! I'm sorry, but I reserve me best prices for those with talent."
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> The old wizard grins. "A simple spell, Charm Person, but you cast it well enough. Come, an artful caster will always get my best prices."
<StartAction>[Invalid Tactic]</Start> Sorry, you are currently unable to cast Charm Person.
<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> "All the more reason to charge you extra," the old man counters.
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> "It comes and goes but I'm afraid I've got poor Raggletag's habits to consider. Better a fair price than none at all."

<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> The old man scowls at you. "We dwarves have been mad as hatters since the days of Brogan, and endlessly proud of our own folly. If I be reborn, I hope it be as an elf..."
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> "Fairer than they would be otherwise," the old man chuckles knowingly. "Provided word of me fine craftings makes it back to your Clan."
<StartAction>[Invalid Tactic]</Start> Sorry, this character will only express kinship towards someone of the same race.
<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> "Harrumph!" The old man scowls at you, insulted by your mockery. "Ye be lucky I don't charge ye double."
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> The old man breaks into a wrinkled smile. "Fine, fine. A discount for making me feel young again." He chuckles to himself.
<StartAction>[Invalid Tactic]</Start> Sorry, this character will only respond to flirtations from the opposite gender.
In a show of his disapproval, the one-armed old dwarf raps the floor with his walking stick. You get the sense that he's haggled more than enough in his long life.
"Come, <lad/lass>, there be no need to haggle. Ye be among friends here and I'll gladly give ye me best prices."
"Goodbye."
"Me have something in funny language. Maybe you help?"
"I could use help translating something..."
"Nothing. Me just curious."
"Nothing. I was just curious."
"Me copy this message in the Guild Exhibits."
"I copied this message in the Guild Exhibits."
"Me find this book where Night Hag lives."
"I found this book in the Night Hag's home."
"You see strangers come through town lately?"
"Have any strangers come through town lately?"
"Me look for Cavanaugh Stone."
"I seek the Cavanaugh Stone."
"Stone makes waters foul?"
"The Stone befouls the water?"
"Uh, can you give example?"
"Can you give me an example?"
"Your well take me to Cavanaugh Stone?"
"Your well leads to the Cavanaugh Stone?"
"Why you say it come from Stygia?"
"Why do you say it's borne of Stygia?"
"Why it be foolish to revere it?"
"Why is it foolish to revere it?"
"Where your arm disappear to?"
"What happened to your arm?"
"Why you try to collapse mines?"
"Why were you trying to collapse the mines?"
"What the exhibits not tell?"
"What don't the exhibits tell?"
"But roof still fall in and trap demons, yuh?"
"But the mines still collapsed to thwart the demons?"
"Where the demons go?"
"Where did the demons go?"
"You be magic dealer?"
"You deal in magic?"
"Back to other questions, okay?"
"Back to my other questions."
"Me have questions 'bout magic stuff."
"I have some questions about the dark arts."
"You ever see an Ethereal Leak?"
"Have you ever seen an Ethereal Leak?"
"What sacrifice you mean?"
"What do you mean, my sacrifice?"
"But me can see them!"
"But I can see them..."
"Uh, no thanks. It sound like too much trouble."
"No thanks. It sounds like too much bother."
"Gimme the device and me think about it, okay?"
"Give me this device and I'll think about it."
"Yuh, okay,"
"Yes, of course."
"Tell me 'bout the Land of Dead."
"Tell me about the Land of the Dead."
"And what those things be?"
"And what things are those?"
"You know the Night Hag, yuh?"
"Do you know the Night Hag?"
"What you mean she be of the fey?'"
"The fey? What do you mean?"
"Yuh? What that be?"
"And what's that?"
"You have raven?"
"You have a raven?"
"Why? What this contraption do?"
"Why? What does the contraption do?"
"It make gold from thin air? For real?"
"It really spins gold from thin air?"
"If found where she gets her gold."
"She was stealing from beneath the Elkentree."
"I found your raven."
"She was stealing gold from beneath the Elkentree."
"Why? What does the contraption do?"
"It really spins gold from thin air?"
